<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1940-10-16T13:22:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1940-10-15T16:00:00-05:00" n="413" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d413">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">823.248/245: Telegram</note>
                        <head><hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in Peru</hi> (<persName type="from"><hi rend="italic">Norweb</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to
                                the <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss></hi></head>
                        <opener>
                            <dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Lima</hi></placeName>, [<date ana="#date_undated-inferred-from-document-content" calendar="gregorian" notAfter="1940-10-16T13:22:00-05:00" notBefore="1940-10-15T16:00:00-05:00">undated</date>].<lb/>[Received October 16—1:22 p.m.]</dateline>
                        </opener>
                        <p>552. My telegram No. 551, October 15, 4 p.m. Radio broadcasts from the
                            United States report Colonel Revoredo as having publicly stated that the
                            diversion of these airplanes is “a most unfriendly act”. Nothing has
                            been published in the press here … The Department’s comment will be
                            appreciated. Feeling in aviation circles is running high.</p>
                        <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">Norweb</hi></signed></closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>